post_text: Training for health staff and LVNs is underway for specimen collection for the new COVID-19 School Testing Sites. These sites will provide additional access to timely testing and results (48-72 hours) and will help Placer County meet the California Department of Public Health recommended testing guidance for schools. “We all want to see students and staff safely back in classrooms as soon as we can, and the opening of these School Testing Sites is a crucial step forward in making that happen,” said Placer County Superintendent Gayle Garbolino-Mojica.

post_text:
Today, the California Department of Education released a guiding document for the safe reopening of public schools. Additionally, the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention and the California Department of Public Health also published industry guidance for schools.

These documents, along with feedback and concerns from students and parents, will help guide local decisions about what learning looks like in the future. School districts can determine, in collaboration with state and local health officials to the extent possible, whether and how to implement these considerations while adjusting to meet the unique needs and circumstances of their local school communities.

Safety is the highest priority and school leaders are working on multiple scenarios in preparation for the start of school in the fall. As a reminder, school districts and charter schools will communicate official plans and details directly to families. #goldineducation

Here's a great summer opportunity for student leaders - the Ed100 Online Summer Academy. Conducted from July 20-22, 2020 (with an optional session on the 23rd), this virtual conference designed just for students and will put you "in the same room" with California experts and leaders who have deep experience and context. You will learn from them directly, with the opportunity to ask your own questions. California's education system is complex: they will help you untangle it so that you can begin the next school year well-informed and ready to make a difference.

APPLY ONLINE: https://ed100.org/blog/student-leader-academy

post_text:
Placer County school leaders in concurrence with Placer County Public Health extend closures of all public schools and state preschools in Placer County through May 1, 2020 in order to slow the spread of COVID-19 to the maximum extent possible. Read the press release: bit.ly/PlacerSchoolsExtClosure

Parents, students and families will continue to receive updates and information from their school districts and charter schools regularly through email, by phone and through social media. School facilities will stay open to staff for essential tasks, and education will continue through district distance learning plans. Schools will continue to provide meals and childcare, when possible.

The Placer County Office of Education's Childcare Resource and Referral Program is available for families working in essential services. Call (530) 745-1380 for assistance.
#goldineducation #wearepcoe

post_text:
Placer County Superintendent of Schools Gayle Garbolino-Mojica, school district superintendents and charter school operators have decided in concurrence with Placer County Public Health to close all public schools and state preschools in Placer County for the next three weeks* in order to protect the health and safety of students and school communities. (*Please note, given various spring break schedules, families should refer to their school district for specific dates of school closures.)

“Decisions like this are difficult to make, but we are taking this action based on what is known at this time about the transmission and severity of the illness to best protect our school communities,” said Superintendent Garbolino-Mojica. “The most effective way to slow the transmission of this virus is to implement social distancing practices. We won’t take chances when it comes to the health and safety of our students.”

Read the full press release: http://bit.ly/PlacerSchoolsClose

#goldineducation #wearepcoe

On January 22, 2020 former Placer County Superintendent of Schools Ken Lonergan passed away at the age of 92. Having served from 1967 to 1987, he started the 49er ROP program and was instrumental in establishing Schools Insurance Group (SIG) and the Placer-Nevada Special Education Local Plan Area (SELPA).

This photo was taken at the 2007 dedication of the Onorato Education Center with former Placer County Superintendent of Schools Ken Lonergan, John Reinking, Bud Nobili and current Placer County Superintendent of Schools Gayle Garbolino-Mojica.

Read more about Ken Lonergan and post to his tribute wall: https://www.cochranewagemann.com/obituaries/Kenneth-L-Lonergan?obId=10727653

There are currently no cases of novel coronavirus in Placer County and the risk of contracting the novel coronavirus in Placer County is deemed to be low at this time. There is no immediate threat to the general public in Placer County, and no special precautions are recommended (such as wearing face masks). People should not be excluded from activities based on their race or country of origin. Placer County residents, students, workers, and visitors should continue to engage in their regular activities and practice good public health hygiene.

Placer County Public Health is actively working with local healthcare facilities to monitor, plan and prepare. More information and resources: https://www.placer.ca.gov/6367/Novel-Coronavirus-2019-nCoV

post_text:
Professional Development Opportunity for K-12 Teachers, Administrators, Coaches and TOSA's: Assessment-Capable Learners on Feb 5, 2020 at The Grounds with guest speaker Doug Fisher, professor of educational leadership at San Diego State University.

We all know that collective efficacy is the new number one influence on students’ learning. And there is good reason for that. In part, efficacious teachers ensure their students are assessment-capable, which means students understand their current level of performance and compare that with the desired level of learning. Join us to learn more: https://placercoe.gosignmeup.com/public/Course/browse?courseid=6611
text:
Professional Development Opportunity for K-12 Teachers, Administrators, Coaches and TOSA's: Assessment-Capable Learners on Feb 5, 2020 at The Grounds with guest speaker Doug Fisher, professor of educational leadership at San Diego State University.

We all know that collective efficacy is the new number one influence on students’ learning. And there is good reason for that. In part, efficacious teachers ensure their students are assessment-capable, which means students understand their current level of performance and compare that with the desired level of learning. Join us to learn more: https://placercoe.gosignmeup.com/public/Course/browse?courseid=6611

post_text:
As we head into the New Year, I am reminded of all the things I am grateful for. Of course, my family and my friends whom I hold dear to my heart. But also, I reflect on the many successes and accomplishments of the Placer County Office of Education this past year. We launched a new website, celebrated our Teachers and Classified School Employees of the Year, honored schools for making meaningful change to student culture through PBIS, embarked on numerous grant-funded endeavors to support and implement Universal Design for Learning, led the way for the school-based behavioral health collaboration and served as the geographic lead for differentiated support.

Our resolutions for the year ahead remain the same - to equip every child with a first-class education to succeed in a global economy, to appreciate the cultural, social and historical resources of their community, and to be active participants in civic responsibilities.

Holiday greetings and joyful wishes for a peaceful and prosperous New Year!

Yours in education,
Gayle Garbolino-Mojica
Placer County Superintendent of Schools

The Twelve Days of Data continues: On the seventh day of data, my data geek gave to me...Court and Community School outcomes.

The Juvenile Court and Community Schools (JCCS) are established through the cooperative efforts of the Placer County Office of Education, local school districts, the Placer County Probation Department and the Placer County Special Multi-Agency Administration and Resource Team. Of those students served who are English Language Learners, 23% were reclassified as English Proficient last year. #goldineducation

Welcome to the 12 Days of Data! For the final 12 days of 2019, we'll be sharing data about Placer County education. We'll celebrate the academic achievements of our students and share information on where we want to continue to grow our future.

On the first day of data, my data geek gave to me...65% of Placer County students met or exceeded the English-Language Arts (ELA) standards on the 2019 California Assessment of Student Performance and Progress (CAASPP).

This is a 2% increase over 2017, and more than 14% over the statewide scores. #goldineducation #12daysofdata

JOB POSTING: We are currently looking for a VI Teacher for our Visually Impaired Program.

Please apply on EDJOIN at https://lnkd.in/dnDwGRv

Application packets must contain the following to be considered complete:
EDJOIN Application
Cover Letter
Resume
Three Letters of Recommendation (with wet ink signatures and dated within the last 24 months)
Proof of an appropriate California teaching credential authorizing specialized services to students with visual impairment
Proof of, or have the ability to obtain, English Learner Authorization
Additional Salary Information:
MA/MS: $1,500 Annual
#teacher #students #wearepcoe
